        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose for a single continuum pointing in Band 9 towards the nearby pulsar Geminga. The candidate dust disc is expected to have a diameter of ~0.2-1 arcsec and a total flux ~32 mJy. With ~0.5km baselines, the resolution elements will be 0.2 arcsec and the maximum diameter fits easily within the largest imageable scale. 

The faintest surface brightness is 1.6 mJy/pixel in the case of a face-on disc of diameter 1 arcsec covering 20 pixels. With an rms of 0.4 mJy/pixel, the mean detection is 4-sigma/pixel in this worst case. The simulation shown is based on this rms after 32 minutes on-source, with Briggs weighting and primary beam correction. The CLEANed image has been rebinned to 0.2 arcsec pixels. The brightest case is a 1-pixel point source of 32 mJy, in which case the source is detected at ~80 sigma. 

The ACA is not selectable for 0.5km baselines at 17deg-North. We intend to fill in large spatial scales by combining the Band-9 ALMA and SCUBA-2 datasets at the reduction stage. The SCUBA-2 image samples scales from 7.8 arcsec (PSF FWHM) up to 3 arcmin (scan FOV). Parts of a larger spiral structure are seen in this wider-field image, but the next-closest flux peak is ~10 arcsec away (Figure 1), and so at ~minimum power in the 12m primary beams.  
 
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
