    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Planets and asteroids can survive post-main-sequence stellar evolution, as seen in the case
of some white dwarfs. However, a massive star that becomes a supernova will destroy its
planetary system. It has been proposed that a second generation of planets can form from a
circum-neutron star disc, but none of these discs have been found. We have recently made an 
unexpected detection at 0.45 mm of continuum emission associated with the nearby pulsar
Geminga. It appears that this is ~3 M(Earth) of dust recently swept up from the interstellar
medium, and potentially in a compact disc. We propose with ALMA to image this disc
candidate, and from the size and mass of dust, see if there is a real capability for a 
second epoch of planet formation around the pulsar. </prp:abstract>
